⁣
This week, I was searching through my ancient Yahoo inbox to find a copy of my diploma, which is apparently a requirement to sign up for this wine class I’ve wanted to take forever. (It’s at @wsetglobal. I really would like to learn more about wine, and my friend @remdelacreme_ took it last year and now she can explain what we’re drinking, which is fun!) I stumbled across an email from this date in 2010: it was my acceptance letter to NYU. Twelve years ago today, I learned I could move to New York. It wasn’t just my first choice; it was the only school I applied to and the only place I wanted to live. (I would’ve applied elsewhere in late December if needed, I wasn’t *that* dramatic.)⁣
⁣
Feeling ~ sentimental ~, I found these photos from shortly after my move in August 2011. I was trying so hard to look like my understanding of a New Yorker: I’d dyed my hair dark (and clearly did the worst, streakiest job), wore all black, pretended I could handle heels like that all day and night. ⁣
⁣
I feel a lot more like myself now — and after a decade-plus, I think I’ve earned my New Yorker card (though I’ll forever be jealous of natives like Eloise). But I miss some of the magic that only happens when you live somewhere new for the first time.⁣
⁣
On my way to dinner tonight, I walked by my old dorm on East 12th Street, my first home here. A girl came out, clip-clopping through the rain in leather pants and too-tall shoes. Wherever she’s going, I hope she has a magical night.

2022 had a lot of big moments, but this little one from April was one of my favorites. Life has no greater pleasure than doing your makeup while listening to Ariana Grande and drinking wine with your favorite person. Not one! More of this in 2023, please.

My workshops are back! In 2021, I got into teaching classes about how to get published — specifically, how to land an agent. I missed running them. I I really love chatting with other writers, especially when it comes to peeling back the curtain on the notoriously opaque publishing industry. ⁣
⁣
If you want to be traditionally published (i.e. by a publishing house, not self-published), you should absolutely have an agent. Not only can your agent negotiate the best possible deal for you, but they're also invaluable resources when it comes to giving feedback on your work, communicating with your editor, and navigating the industry. It's rare for an editor to buy a book straight from an author, so a good agent is crucial. ⁣
⁣
My next workshop will be on Monday, January 30 at 6:30 p.m. ET for $50. It'll be virtual. We'll talk about how to create a list of agents to target, the art of the perfect query letter, red flags and green flags from meetings with agents, and plenty more. ⁣
⁣
To register, head to the link in my bio! ⁣
⁣
#aspiringauthor⁣ #writingcommunity #writersofinstagram #writingtips #writinginspiration #publishinglife #bookpublishing #writingclasses

Happy Galentine's Day! ❤️ I threw a party to celebrate my favorite day of the year. We had gals, glitter, and *Looks* with a capital L. 💃🏻 An entire fridge full of wine poured into mismatched glasses. 🍷 Brown sugar cake with cranberry jam and buttercream frosting. 🍰Streamers, candles, flowers, a playlist full of pop divas. ✨ I only burned one appetizer to a charred crisp! ⁣
⁣
The highlight of the night was the sexy storytelling competition. Per tradition, anyone brave enough to entertain the crowd with a true scandalous story won a prize of their choosing. There were at least three current/former sex and dating editors in the room; the first item snagged was a T-shirt that says "no fake orgasms."⁣
 ⁣
I love this made-up holiday and I love my gals. Until next year! xoxo 💕💕💕

✨ Thirty, flirty, and thriving ✨⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I celebrated the start of a new decade with so many of the people who made my twenties in New York so special. What a night ❤️⁣⁣
⁣⁣
In no particular order, here are 30 life lessons I stand by:⁣⁣
⁣⁣
1. By 30, you should have a therapist, hair stylist, bodega guy, and career mentor you can trust.⁣⁣
2. When you’re just starting out in your career, say yes to everything. The unglamorous tasks opened the biggest doors for me.⁣⁣
3. You know you’ve made it in a new city when you find friends who feel like family.⁣⁣
4. It’s okay — and probably good for you — to love something you’re not so great at.⁣⁣
5. The best day of the year is the first warm Saturday of spring. Cherish it. Throw a picnic.⁣⁣
6. Block heels are more walkable than flats or stilettos.⁣⁣
7. You didn’t move here to sit at home.⁣⁣
8. Journal, take notes, snap photos, save mementos — someday, you’ll want to remember all this.⁣⁣
9. The one New Year’s resolution you should actually stick to: kicking your Seamless habit.⁣⁣
10. You’re happier when you live near your friends.⁣⁣
11. If you’re in a bad mood, go for a walk and call someone you love.⁣⁣
12. It’s infinitely better to be single than in a bad relationship.⁣⁣
13. If everyone you know thinks you can do better than your boyfriend, you can.⁣⁣
14. Going through shit makes you stronger, wiser, and more empathetic. ⁣⁣
15. You’re probably more resilient than you give yourself credit for.⁣⁣
16. Fun doesn’t just happen — sometimes, you have to make it happen.⁣⁣
17. Everything closes eventually. Don’t take it for granted that your favorite Mexican restaurant or piano bar is still there. Go often.⁣⁣
18. Even if you’re a Type A Taurus who hates change, some of life’s biggest delights start off as disappointing curveballs.⁣
19. Take care of yourself. Always wear sunscreen. You’ll feel better after a meal.⁣⁣
20. Learn from others, then pay it forward.⁣⁣
21. The best $75 you can spend is on a two-pound tuxedo kitten from the ASPCA truck in Union Square.⁣⁣
22. Don’t confuse anxiety for butterflies. Trust your gut.⁣⁣
⁣
Continued in the comments…
This certainly beats eating oatmeal on my couch.
So far, my thirties are pretty good.

For almost a year, Heartbeat has brought you original short love stories from today’s most exciting writers and talented new voices. As rom-com novelists, we love romance and wanted to share the very best of it with you. While we’ve enjoyed the ride, today’s story will be our last.

Between soliciting pitches and sorting through submissions, to the intensive editing of multiple drafts, this project was more work than two already busy women could handle! 

But, don’t go anywhere. If you’ve enjoyed our Three Things recs and the feel-good nature of all-things-romance, you’re in luck. Heartbeat will transform into my monthly author newsletter. I’ll be sharing practical writing advice, pop culture recs, and a behind-the-scenes peek into my publishing journey, each and every month. 

For now, head over to Heartbeat (http://theheartbeat.substack.com) to enjoy revisiting our very first short story, written by yours truly, bringing us full circle.

We’re incredibly grateful to all our writers and readers, and hope we achieved our goal of adding a little love to your Fridays. 

❤️Georgia Clark & Hannah Orenstein❤️

I missed my sister, so I bought a plane ticket to England. I had the best week with her! She introduced me to the very British concept of a "ramble" (wandering around the countryside to admire green fields full of livestock), brought me to a music festival at a club on a boat (more clubs should be on boats!), and gave me the confidence to attempt the world's most ridiculous athletic activity (swipe to the last slide — and no, I will not be doing this again). We watched all of Queen Charlotte in 24 hours and got Sri Lankan food twice because it might be the one cuisine I can't find in New York City.⁣
⁣
We're five years apart and opposites in so many ways: She thrives in new places, I never want to leave New York. Her Instagram account collects dust and I'm very online. She met her boyfriend on a spontaneous snowy camping trip, I don't like to go outside unless I can sunbathe. (And I could go on.) If we weren't related, we probably wouldn't be friends — but I'm so glad we are.
You can take the girl out of Boston, but you can’t take Boston out of the girl. Thank you, @dunkin, for being a total dream and giving me the best day at @govballnyc 💕🧡☕️

Cheers to summer! It’s finally here, we made it to the best part of the year.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
What are your summer plans? First I’m going to Block Island with friends, swinging by Somerville to cheer on my mom during her mini-triathlon, then up to Maine! Prepare for the onslaught of sunset photos just like this one, only without Lady Liberty in the background (more like a pair of loons or a boat playing Bruce Springsteen). ⁣
⁣
If you need July 4th weekend plans, @lovejadot is running an amazing deal: $75 for a two-hour sail around the city, plus five small courses with wine pairings from Burgundy. This isn’t an ad — they just took me on the same cruise and it was *the* perfect New York summer night.
Bye, New York, see you in September ✌🏻

Two things to know about summers at the lake: ⁣
⁣
1. I wear big T-shirts over swimsuits pretty much every day. ⁣
2. We love hosting friends and family here. ⁣
⁣
So, naturally, we ordered an enormous box of custom T-shirts to wear and give out to anyone who visits. I recommend this — it's fun to feel like a hotel doling out fluffy bathrobes. (And also looks... a lot more like a cult? We had a mini family reunion last weekend and it was hilarious to see a dozen people wearing them at once.) ⁣
⁣
I sketched out the idea, my mom brought the graphic design to life, and @rushordertees printed them. (ACME is our nickname for the house.) I'm obsessed with them, they bring me an embarrassing amount of joy. ⁣
⁣
P.S. Special thanks to @atriabooks, whose copy editors taught me over the the course of four books that the proper stylization is "T-shirt" and not "t-shirt." It finally stuck. I've learned!⁣
⁣
📷: @gart_of_clontarff
I don’t see very many people during the summer, but the ones I do see? The best.

THE SUMMER RULES:⁣
⁣
1. Wear SPF, not pants.⁣
2. Stay hydrated.⁣
3. Don’t go inside.

This summer, my dad and I went out onto the lake to watch the sunset almost every single night. In terms of actual visuals, this was the worst year we've ever had. Typically, there are jaw-dropping skies most nights; this year, there was a lot of rain, or the skies were otherwise just kind of meh. But this is the best part of the day, and spending this time with him in our favorite place was the highlight of my season (literally... it's saved as a highlight if you want to see every sunset). ⁣
⁣
We bring out tortilla chips, drinks, sometimes my mom likes to join, sometimes we have friends. I bring my notebook and he brings a magazine, but most of the time, we just discuss the sky the way other families probably discuss sports: comments, critiques, updates, predictions for what will happen next. We bird-watch and came up with a rating system (out of 10 points, one score for the sky, one for the vibes — I'm a softie, @jack0renstein is a tough critic, the Simon Cowell of sunsets). I'm so grateful to be able to do this with him so often.⁣
⁣
To sum up the whole season: ⁣
Sky: 4/10⁣
Vibes: 11/10
POV: summer is not your season.
Raise your hand if you’re obsessed with the sky 🙋🏻‍♀️

My favorite activity in the entire world is sitting outside on the water with a pen and notebook, working on a first draft. No internet, no distractions, no Word doc to easily edit, which I think just gets you bogged down. I type everything up at night and don’t edit until the first draft is done. A lot of it is messy and that’s totally fine. I can fix it later.⁣
⁣
For the first time, I’m writing without a mega outline, and I’m keeping everything organized in Scrivener. I’m not trying to optimize for efficiency or hit a certain word count, but rather, just write for the sheer enjoyment of it. I’m incredibly grateful to be able to write in a setting like this, and I always feel lucky that I’ve found something I love so much.⁣
⁣

Ciao! I spent the past week exploring Italy with my family. I loved the Renaissance art and intricate architecture in Florence; the medieval villages and absurd scenery in Tuscany; the ancient history and fireworks in Rome; the good wine, truffles, and gelato all over the place; and most importantly, closing out 2023 with my favorite people.
